<h2>
    Meet the Brown Trout: Oregon’s Elusive Fighter
</h2>
<p>
    Brown trout (<i>Salmo trutta</i>) are native to Europe but were introduced to Oregon in the early 1900s. Since then, they’ve flourished in the state’s cold, clean waters, especially in deeper reservoirs and shaded streams.
</p>
<h3>
    How to Identify Brown Trout
</h3>
<p>
    Brown trout have:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        A golden-brown body with dark spots surrounded by lighter halos.
    </li>
    <li>
        Red or orange spots along their sides.
    </li>
    <li>
        A pronounced square tail and large jaw, particularly in mature males.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    They’re masters of camouflage, often hiding beneath logs, rocks, or undercut banks where they ambush prey.
</p>
<h3>
    Habitat and Behavior Patterns
</h3>
<p>
    Brown trout thrive in cool, oxygen-rich water. They’re primarily nocturnal feeders, targeting insects, small fish, and crustaceans. In Oregon, they prefer deep pools and shaded stretches of rivers with moderate currents. Near Salem, look for them in clear tributaries, reservoir inlets, and deeper channels of the North Santiam River.
</p>
