</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Short-term licenses:</strong> Available for visitors or weekend anglers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Annual licenses:</strong> Offer the best value for frequent fishing trips.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Always keep your license with you, whether you’re fishing from shore, a boat, or a float tube.
</p>
<h3>
    Conservation Tips
</h3>
<p>
    Although brown trout are non-native in Oregon, many fisheries maintain self-sustaining populations that deserve protection.
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Practice catch and release:</strong> Especially for large, wild trout. Use barbless hooks and wet your hands before handling fish.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Minimize stress:</strong> Land fish quickly and avoid removing them from the water unnecessarily.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Respect spawning areas:</strong> During fall (October–November), browns spawn in shallow gravel beds—avoid wading through these areas.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Responsible angling ensures that Oregon’s brown trout waters remain vibrant for future generations.
